From: quinlan@plum.cs.bucknell.edu (Daniel Quinlan)
Subject: Re: Please do NOT reply mail
Date: 25 Oct 1993 01:36:21 GMT
Reply-To: quinlan@spectrum.cs.bucknell.edu


iwj10@cus.cam.ac.uk (Ian Jackson) writes:

>>If you do not have read access to Usenet you should not post.
>>Period.

vince@victrola.wa.com (Vince Skahan) said:

> [...I'm so tired of USENET and its ridiculous 'keepers of what is
> right and proper'...]

> Ian, you have made some nice contributions to Linux, but you are totally
> and consistently full of shit on this subject (IMHO).

Ian is right on this one.  Ever hear of the "Golden Rule"?  This
should be a corollary - "Don't expect something from others which you
are not prepared to give yourself."

> There is nothing either wrong or rude in people asking for followups
> via mail.  If you can't deal with their request to 'not followup',
> don't answer the stinking question.  There are many, many other
> people who will and the guy will get the answer eventually anyway.

Then there must be nothing wrong with ignoring such arrogant requests.
There ARE other resources for answering questions that Ian spends
*his* time bringing to our attention.  You just complain about it.  I
consider his time more valuable to the Linux community than yours.

People should make use of them rather than waste other people's time.
When you take 1 minute to post an asinine question, upwards of 1000 or
5000 people will spend 10-20 seconds to decide it was stupid and
perhaps 10 will take the time to reply (when the question could be
answered by RTFM.)

> Ian, please give it a rest and give us all a break.

[low]  "my" minute -> 1000 * 1/6 = 167 minutes
[high] "my" minute -> 5000 * 1/3 = 1667 minutes

Could all the people wasting our time out there RTFM and give us all a
break?

[best] "my" hour reading the FAQ -> 60 minutes
[best] "my" 5 minute period scanning the FAQ for one answer -> 5 minutes

// Dan
--
Daniel Quinlan  <quinlan@spectrum.cs.bucknell.edu>

