From: iiitac@swan.pyr (Alan Cox)
Subject: Re: etherfind?
Date: Mon, 25 Oct 1993 10:03:59 GMT

In article <1993Oct22.183600.3332@super.org> becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker) writes:
>In article <55590@sdcc12.ucsd.edu>,
>Ian McCloghrie <imcclogh@cs.ucsd.edu> wrote:
>>
>>      Does anyone know of anything similar to Sun's etherfind for linux?
>>Would be quite useful in diagnosing networking problems :)
>
>Linux networking doesn't yet have "promiscuous mode", which is needed by most
>network watch tools.  I've just implemented the device level hooks for
>promiscuous/multicast in my ethercard device drivers(*), but the socket-level
>code still needs to be written.
It's done and should be in pl13k. There are some important warnings however.

Do NOT have any ip routes etc setup on the promiscuous mode interface if you
have IP_FORWARD enabled. The IP code doesn't understand the promiscuous mode
to tell and becomes a rather busy gateway. I'll fix this soonish. 

Apart from that its great. I've been monitoring and debugging my Linux IPX
stuff with the code. 

Alan
iiitac@pyr.swan.ac.uk


